'''Code Louisville''' is a [[public–private partnership]] program in [[Louisville, Kentucky]] with the aim of fostering [[software developer]]s to bolster technological innovation in the region.<ref name="About">{{cite web|url=http://www.codelouisville.org/about/|title=Code Louisville - About|work=codelouisville.org|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150407155845/http://www.codelouisville.org/about/|archivedate=2015-04-07|df=}}</ref> It received national attention in April 2015 when President [[Barack Obama]] visited the region to announce [[TechHire]]<ref name="marissaalter">{{cite web|url=http://www.wlky.com/news/president-obama-delays-departure-to-louisville/32151936|title=President Obama rallies support for job training in Louisville|author=Marissa Alter|date=4 December 2013|work=WLKY}}</ref> and promote the value of the [[United States federal government|federal government]] working with [[local government]]s.<ref name="wfpl.org">{{cite web|url=http://wfpl.org/president-obama-wants-programs-like-code-louisville/|title=President Obama Wants More Programs Like Code Louisville|work=89.3 WFPL}}</ref>
==Purpose== Code Louisville is a public–private partnership program in Louisville that began in November 2013.<ref name="wfpl.org1">{{cite web|url=http://wfpl.org/code-louisville-aims-expand-regions-available-tech-talent/|title=Code Louisville Aims to Expand the Region's Available Tech Talent - 89.3 WFPL|work=89.3 WFPL}}</ref> [[Metro Louisville]] Department of Economic Growth and Innovation, [[Greater Louisville Inc.]], [[EnterpriseCorp]], the [[Louisville Free Public Library]], and [[KentuckianaWorks]] are partnered with local employers partner who hire graduates of the program.<ref name="About" /> It is a free 12-week online [[computer programming|coding]] course open to those with a [[library card]].<ref name="wfpl.org"/><ref name="wfpl.org1"/><ref name="wfpl.org2">{{cite web|url=http://wfpl.org/why-louisvilles-tech-initiatives-are-on-a-national-stage-today/|title=Why Louisville's Tech Initiatives Are on a National Stage Today|work=89.3 WFPL}}</ref> It aims to foster [[software developer]]s in the area, so as to bolster a technological innovation in the region.<ref name="About" /> The program works in collaboration with [[Treehouse (company)|Treehouse]],<ref name="wfpl.org1"/> including a prerequisite course.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.codelouisville.org/candidates/|title=Code Louisville - Candidates|work=codelouisville.org|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150407165630/http://www.codelouisville.org/candidates/|archivedate=2015-04-07|df=}}</ref>
==Effectiveness== The program has been lauded for its success compared to similar programs in other cities.<ref name="wfpl.org2"/> In April 2015, President Obama visited Louisville to praise the program and to use it as an example of the federal TechHire initiative that provides grants to similar programs.<ref name="marissaalter"/><ref name="wfpl.org"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.yahoo.com/obama-rallies-support-job-training-224747543.html|title=Obama rallies support for job training over tax cuts|date=2 April 2015|work=Yahoo News}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.msnbc.com/shift/watch/live-obama-talks-economy-in-louisville-422021699891|title=President Obama talks economy in Louisville|work=MSNBC}}</ref> In 2015, it was announced that Code Louisville would attempt to create a program to teach others cities how to run similar programs.<ref name="wfpl.org2"/>
