[[File:Oenothera depressa 20050829 334 part.jpg|thumb|Oenothera sp. that experiences tachyspory]] '''Tachyspory''' is a form of [[Dehiscence (botany)|dehiscence]] where seed is rapidly released from a [[Conifer cone|cone]] or [[fruit]] upon maturity, as opposed to [[Bradyspory]], the slow release of seed over time.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=pK_xCAAAQBAJ&pg=PA100&lpg=PA100&dq=tachyspory&source=bl&ots=Nd4typ5b2b&sig=n_0MHmpcku250gxsqM_tNOjcmCY&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwi5553d-JjcAhXrwFQKHTtaDh0Q6AEIPjAE#v=onepage&q=tachyspory&f=false|title=Principles of Dispersal in Higher Plants|last=Pijl|first=L. van der|date=2012-12-06|publisher=Springer Science & Business Media|isbn=9783642879258|language=en}}</ref> It is a word used in [[botany]] to describe seed dispersal.
"Tachy" is a word-forming element meaning "rapid, swift, fast," from Latinized comb. form of Greek takhy "swift."<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.dictionary.com/browse/tachy-|title=the definition of tachy-|website=www.dictionary.com|language=en|access-date=2018-07-12}}</ref>
